This is a request on behalf of The James Madison Project (“JMP”) and Adam Entous (hereinafter referred to jointly as “the Requesters”) under the Freedom of Information Act, 5 U.S.C. § 552, et seq. In August 2017, media outlets began reporting that U.S. Government officials working in the U.S. Embassy in Havana, Cuba, were subjected to an “acoustic attack” that resulted in health problems. https://www.cnn.com/2017/08/09/politics/us-cuba-acoustic-attack-embassy/index.html (last accessed December 10, 2020). The attacks began in mid-November 2016 and lasted until Spring 2017, forcing U.S. Government officials and their family members to seek medical treatment. https://www.cnn.com/2017/08/20/politics/havana-sonic-attacks/index.html (last accessed December 10, 2020). President Trump has publicly stated that he believes the Cuban Government is responsible for the attacks. https://www.cnn.com/2017/10/16/politics/trump-cuba-us-diplomats-attack/index.html (last accessed December 10, 2020). On January 12, 2018, then-Secretary of State Rex Tillerson convened an independent Accountability Review Board (“ARB”) to review the circumstances surrounding the medical and health problems being reported. The finalized ARB Report was submitted to Congress on August 30, 2018, outlining recommendations and actions take in response. https://www.state.gov /r/pa/prs/ps/2018/08/285576.htm (last accessed December 10, 2020). The National Academy of Sciences completed a report (hereinafter referred to as the “Report”) assessing the potential causes of what is known as the “Havana Syndrome”. https://www.gq.com/story/cia-investigation-and-russian-microwave-attacks (last accessed December 10, 2020); https://www.nytimes.com/2020/10/19/us/politics/diplomat-attacks-havana-syndrome.html?referringSource=articleShare (last accessed December 10, 2020). That report has now been made public. https://www.nbcnews.com/news/all/havana-syndrome-likely-caused-microwave-energy-government-study-finds-n1250094 (last accessed December 10, 2020). In the Report, reference is made to a separate final report designated as the CUBA Unexplained Events Investigation (“Investigation”), conducted by the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (“CDC”). The Report states that on April 28, 2020, the Investigation was received by the Department of State’s Standing Committee to Advise the Department of State on Unexplained Health Effects on U.S. Government Employees and Their Families at Overseas Embassies. The Requesters seek copies of records created, received and/or maintained by the CDC, including cross-references. Specifically, the Requesters are seeking the following: 1) A copy of the Investigation in its entirety, including all appendices, exhibits and addendum (if any); and 2) To the extent they are not encompassed by line item #1, any correspondence within CDC or between CDC and other U.S. Government agencies outlining steps that will be taken or have already been taken to implement the recommendations or findings of the Investigation CDC should ensure that its search for responsive records encompasses Government civilian employees, detailees, political appointees, Constitutional officers, and contract staff. The scope of CDC’s searches should include, but not be limited to, e-mail communications on unclassified and classified systems, as well as records stored on individual hard drives and/or shared drives. CDC can limit the timeframe of its searches from November 1, 2016, up until the date upon which CDC begins conducting searches for responsive records. The scope of the searches should not be limited to CDC-originated records and should be construed to include records that are currently in the possession of a U.S. Government contractor for purposes of records management
